telling you a little story.

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:45.370
And this is a story
about a leading law

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:48.100
firm based in New York.

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:50.600
The senior team at the law
firm noticed something peculiar

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:52.400
happening a few years ago.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:54.600
They noticed that the
youngest associates

00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:56.940
at the firm, the
millennial associates,

00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:59.840
started to bill less
hours than ever before.

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:02.440
And this was quite peculiar,
because, one, they were giving

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:04.210
them more work, not less work.

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:07.110
And two is we all know law
firms bill by the hour.

00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:09.080
So it was actually a concern.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:10.880
And so when they
dug into it, they

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:14.670
discovered that actually these
millennial legal associates had

00:02:14.670 --> 00:02:16.400
created their own
Twitter network

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:20.250
to help each other solve
cases faster, questions like,

00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:21.470
I need this legal citation.

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:22.886
Does anyone know
where to find it?

00:02:22.886 --> 00:02:25.410
Or, I know we did a case in
law school just like this.

00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:26.770
What was the name of it?

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:29.850
And it became such a rapidly
productive community that it

00:02:29.850 --> 00:02:31.930
was changing the bottom line.

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:34.200
But the story actually
doesn't stop there.

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:37.890
The legal firm has now taken
on an initiative called Twitter

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:41.210
at Work to help teach
everyone at the law firm

00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:43.360
how to better use these tools.

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:45.630
But there's one flip
side to the story,

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:49.170
and that's the fact that
these young associates get

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:51.590
promoted through billing hours.

00:02:51.590 --> 00:02:54.540
So the way that they're working
in a more productive way

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:56.700
is that actually, at the
heart, against the way

00:02:56.700 --> 00:02:59.460
the industry is
still structured.

00:02:59.460 --> 00:03:02.910
So today, we are going
to talk about a rising

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:04.920
change in the future of work.

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.520
And this is a
change that is being

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:10.650
embodied by the rise of the
multi-generational workplace.

00:03:10.650 --> 00:03:13.880
We have four generations
in the workplace today.

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:17.450
And generations are simply
a manifestation of the way

00:03:17.450 --> 00:03:18.910
that the world is changing.

00:03:18.910 --> 00:03:21.460
So when we talk about
Traditionalists, Baby Boomers,

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:25.610
Gen X'ers and Gen Y'ers, also
known as the millennials,

00:03:25.610 --> 00:03:28.130
we aren't just
talking about an age.

00:03:28.130 --> 00:03:30.490
We're actually talking
of a cohort that

00:03:30.490 --> 00:03:33.330
has a set of experiences,
a certain way

00:03:33.330 --> 00:03:36.640
of working, mobilizing people,
solving problems, that's

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:40.500
actually a clue to the way work
will be changing in the future.

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:44.740
So let me first highlight this
also with where we're going.

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:48.930
Research shows that 75%
of the world's workforce

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:51.680
will be millennials by 2020.

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:55.240
And I'm here to talk to you
about what really brought me

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:57.750
into this research on
correctional intelligence,

00:03:57.750 --> 00:04:00.400
and it stems from
this question of,

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:03.570
if we think about generations
as a manifestation of the way

00:04:03.570 --> 00:04:05.600
that the world is
changing, just like it

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:10.720
did at the law firm, what's
unique about millennials?

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:12.590
And this is a big
hot topic right now

00:04:12.590 --> 00:04:14.540
that many people are asking.

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:16.510
And what I'm
actually here to say

00:04:16.510 --> 00:04:19.260
is that often what
you hear about what's

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:22.440
unique about millennials
isn't actually true.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:25.480
And when you ask, what you
hear from what millennials

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:27.600
might say they
want might actually

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:29.890
be contradicted in action.

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:32.510
So let me explain.

00:04:32.510 --> 00:04:36.130
Research shows that
72% of millennials

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:38.590
want to have ownership
or to be their own boss.

00:04:38.590 --> 00:04:41.750
But when we actually look at
where the next generation goes

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:43.740
when they leave a
large organization,

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:46.900
they actually more often don't
just start their own company.

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:50.070
They go and join another
small or large organization.

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:52.090
So having entire
ownership or being

00:04:52.090 --> 00:04:56.460
your entirely own boss
isn't unique to millennials.

00:04:56.460 --> 00:04:58.670
The second thing
that we've heard

00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:01.730
is that 88% of
millennials desire

00:05:01.730 --> 00:05:04.180
a viable work-life integration.

00:05:04.180 --> 00:05:07.530
And while work-life is
incredibly important,

00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:10.510
if you actually look at
the Fortune 500 companies

00:05:10.510 --> 00:05:13.650
and you look at the best
work-life flexibility programs,

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:18.230
you actually see that there
is not a significant decrease

00:05:18.230 --> 00:05:20.620
in turnover among young talent.

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:24.240
So while work-life integration
it is a great perk,

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:26.120
it actually is something
that we all want,

00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:28.490
and it's not unique to
millennials in terms

00:05:28.490 --> 00:05:31.550
of why they stay at a company.

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:35.970
The third thing we hear is
that 88 of the next generation

00:05:35.970 --> 00:05:38.220
desire a collaborative
work culture.

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:40.890
And collaborative work
cultures are fantastic, just

00:05:40.890 --> 00:05:42.390
like one here Google.

00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:46.070
But again, when we look at
the research, what we find

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:49.110
is that there isn't a
significant decrease

00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:52.300
in turnover looking at
the best companies that

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:55.560
have the highest rated
collaborative work cultures.

00:05:55.560 --> 00:05:58.100
So again, ladies and
gentlemen, that's not unique to

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:59.450
millennials.

00:05:59.450 --> 00:06:03.190
And fourth, we hear
that 74% of millennials

00:06:03.190 --> 00:06:05.120
desire a lot of flexibility.

00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:09.590
But again, if we look at the
top companies around the world,

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:12.920
flexibility programs have
remained a perk but not a game

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:16.640
changer when we really
talk about fully engaging

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:20.070
our best talent and retaining
them in the workplace today.

00:06:20.070 --> 00:06:25.150
So, ladies and gentlemen, what
is unique about millennials?

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:32.270
I want to start by quoting a
famous quote by Henry Ford.

00:06:32.270 --> 00:06:35.700
Henry Ford said, if I had
asked people what they wanted,

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:37.900
they would have
said, faster horses.

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:39.860
And I'm actually here to
kick this off and say,

00:06:39.860 --> 00:06:41.840
if we look at the
future of work,

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:45.150
oftentimes what we hear isn't
exactly what people mean.

00:06:45.150 --> 00:06:47.860
And when actually
making a decision,

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:49.950
it could look actually
quite different.

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:52.970
But I do want to say that
there is one thing that

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:56.050
is unique to the future work
mindset that's manifested

00:06:56.050 --> 00:06:59.120
by millennials but is really
used by all generations

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:00.730
in the workforce today.

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:02.800
And what I want to say
is that it's not only

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:06.060
a core competency of
the future of work,

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:08.340
but it's a core
competency in reaching

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:11.760
your customers, clients,
and other stakeholders more

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:15.170
intelligently in the
next wave of the century.

00:07:15.170 --> 00:07:18.970
And that is what my
coauthor Saj-Nicole Joni

00:07:18.970 --> 00:07:21.960
and I call connectional
intelligence.

00:07:21.960 --> 00:07:24.590
Connectional intelligence
is the ability

00:07:24.590 --> 00:07:28.870
to combine knowledge,
ambition, and human capital,

00:07:28.870 --> 00:07:31.450
forging connections
on a global scale that

00:07:31.450 --> 00:07:35.010
create unprecedented
value and meaning.

00:07:35.010 --> 00:07:37.420
So what does this
look like in action?

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:38.795
I'm going to start
by telling you

00:07:38.795 --> 00:07:43.290
a story of some unimaginable
transformations and examples

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:45.250
of connectional intelligence.

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:49.500
The first is about a
grandmother, right up there.

00:07:49.500 --> 00:07:53.670
And this grandmother is part of
a unique cadre of grandmothers

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:54.930
called The Granny Cloud.

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:56.490
Has anyone heard of
the Granny Cloud?

00:07:56.490 --> 00:07:58.770
Raise your hand if you have.

00:07:58.770 --> 00:07:59.270
No?

00:07:59.270 --> 00:08:03.920
So the Granny Cloud is a cadre
of grandmothers in the UK

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:06.570
and Australia who
use video Skype

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:10.270
to Skype weekly with Indian
children throughout India.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:12.650
And it all started
through an experiment

00:08:12.650 --> 00:08:15.300
that a professor named
Sugata Mitra ran.

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:19.710
This was an experiment where
he embedded computer kiosks

00:08:19.710 --> 00:08:23.580
with Wi-Fi into slum
areas throughout India.

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:26.190
And what he wanted to see is,
if you just left the computer

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:27.310
there, what would happen?

00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:28.890
How would the children use it?

00:08:28.890 --> 00:08:30.770
And what he saw is
that when he came back

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:34.580
a month or two months later,
the young children had entirely

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.940
learned how to use a
computer themselves.

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:38.309
And they were getting online.

00:08:38.309 --> 00:08:39.940
There was Wi-Fi enabled.

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:42.110
And the first thing
that they tried to do

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:44.900
was to learn English and
practice their English.

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:47.440
So while this started to
get momentum and these

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:51.440
hole-in-the-wall kiosks started
to spread and also to get known

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.750
around the world, there was a
group of grandmothers in the UK

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:56.970
that said, hey, we
want to help, too.

00:08:56.970 --> 00:09:03.160
And when you think of help
from the original context,

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:04.870
you'd ask these
grandmothers for money.

00:09:04.870 --> 00:09:07.100
But they said, we
want to do more.

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:10.080
And so they created the
Granny Cloud in partnership

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:12.580
with Sugata Mitra's team.

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:16.150
And today, there are
hundreds of grandmothers

00:09:16.150 --> 00:09:17.900
around the world that
are using the Granny

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:20.410
Cloud not only to connect with
each other through a Facebook

00:09:20.410 --> 00:09:22.990
group and an email
newsletter, but to connect

00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:25.210
through video Skype
with these children.

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:26.990
And you think that
the story stops there

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:28.710
and the grandmothers
are the givers.

00:09:28.710 --> 00:09:30.220
But actually, it doesn't.

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:32.460
In fact, research
is now being done

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:36.930
to show that video interaction
with grandmothers and those

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:39.360
at elderly age
actually increases

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:42.800
their cognitive ability
as they decline.

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:46.110
So the Granny Cloud,
again, is not only

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:49.290
creating a one-way form of
connectional intelligence,

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:52.390
but it's truly creating
a two-way connectivity

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:55.200
engagement that is
transforming people's lives

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:56.680
around the world.

00:09:56.680 --> 00:09:58.750
The second story I want
to share is a story

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:03.020
about Patrick Meier who
ran an initiative called

00:10:03.020 --> 00:10:04.510
Ushahidi-Haiti.

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:08.060
Patrick spent two years
in Haiti before going back

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:11.960
to Tufts University grad school,
the Fletcher School there.

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:16.430
And back a few years ago when
the Haiti earthquake hit,

00:10:16.430 --> 00:10:19.230
he was at Tufts in
Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:22.520
But he was extremely
overwhelmed,

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:24.580
and he was instantly
trying to reach out

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:26.720
to his friends in
Haiti that were there

00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:27.782
during the earthquake.

00:10:27.782 --> 00:10:29.490
So the first thing
that he started to do,

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:31.600
sitting from his
computer lab at Tufts,

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:33.340
was to start to
track the tweets.

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:36.090
Because half of Haiti had
power, and half of Haiti didn't.

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:38.040
So he tried to track
any tweets that

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:42.210
were coming in from Haiti from
his friends and other people.

00:10:42.210 --> 00:10:47.040
And then he had been a part
of a team that had embedded

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:48.520
something called Ushahidi.

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:51.950
And Ushahidi is basically
Google Maps meets Twitter,

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:54.810
where basically you can track
tweets and text messages

00:10:54.810 --> 00:10:57.790
and map them to the location
where they're coming from.

00:10:57.790 --> 00:11:02.090
So he started to do this by
himself, tracking tweets.

00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:05.320
And then he got a team around
him at Tufts University

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:08.980
to ask others to
engage with him as well

00:11:08.980 --> 00:11:10.720
to track this information.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:14.040
Soon enough, they had built
a map of hundreds of reports.

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:16.180
They not only did that,
they reached out to someone

00:11:16.180 --> 00:11:19.720
through Twitter that was in
Cameroon that knew the largest

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:21.730
telecommunications
company in Haiti

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:26.300
to get a 911-type symbol up
so people could also share

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:28.110
through text message alerts.

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:29.570
And these are
people sharing where

00:11:29.570 --> 00:11:33.080
they were, where survivors
were that needed to be moved

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:35.210
to safer ground and beyond.

00:11:35.210 --> 00:11:37.070
So the next thing
that happened is

00:11:37.070 --> 00:11:41.190
that many of these texts and
tweets were in Haitian Creole.

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:43.590
So what Patrick did sitting
in Cambridge, Massachusetts,

00:11:43.590 --> 00:11:45.450
is he invited the
Haitian diaspora,

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:49.030
the immigrant community, to come
in and translate these tweets

00:11:49.030 --> 00:11:52.790
and created almost a
makeshift, 24/7 operating room

00:11:52.790 --> 00:11:54.730
to track these messages.

00:11:54.730 --> 00:11:57.700
Within just a few
days in that week,

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:59.860
the Marine Corps and
the US Coast Guard

00:11:59.860 --> 00:12:02.870
started to use
Patrick's Ushahidi map

00:12:02.870 --> 00:12:07.430
to both find survivors and
move them to safer ground

00:12:07.430 --> 00:12:10.350
and to even find
survivors that were

00:12:10.350 --> 00:12:12.580
under rubble that
would have never been

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:14.670
saved without Patrick's map.

00:12:14.670 --> 00:12:17.600
And so by connecting a
disparate group of people,

00:12:17.600 --> 00:12:20.506
by using connectivity
and people around him

00:12:20.506 --> 00:12:23.160
in Cambridge,
Massachusetts, he not only

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:25.130
was able to connect with
his friends in Haiti,

00:12:25.130 --> 00:12:27.950
but he was actually able to
save lives in partnership

00:12:27.950 --> 00:12:30.190
with government.

00:12:30.190 --> 00:12:32.190
The third story I
want to share is

00:12:32.190 --> 00:12:35.715
the story of the Oreo
tweet at Super Bowl 2013.

00:12:35.715 --> 00:12:38.164
Has anyone seen this ad before?

00:12:38.164 --> 00:12:39.830
Tell us where it's
