00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:19.740
And so it was at
that time when they

00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:23.140
saw this happen, because they
had naturally been doing this,

00:14:23.140 --> 00:14:26.960
prepare to act fast and be
relevant, that they actually

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:29.270
broke through with this ad.

00:14:29.270 --> 00:14:33.150
And today, brands everywhere
are trying to reinvent and learn

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:35.300
from this, because
it truly is flipping

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:37.610
the mindset of how
marketers will market

00:14:37.610 --> 00:14:40.000
at big events in the future.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.190
And the fourth story
I want to tell you

00:14:42.190 --> 00:14:44.750
is the story of the
Doritos guacamole chip.

00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:46.330
They're delicious, by the way.

00:14:46.330 --> 00:14:48.770
But I actually want
to ask you first,

00:14:48.770 --> 00:14:52.610
when you think of a Doritos
guacamole chip, what department

00:14:52.610 --> 00:14:55.480
at Frito Lay would
come up with this chip,

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:56.980
would create this chip?

00:14:56.980 --> 00:14:59.100
Tell me.

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:02.222
R&amp;D, yep, R&amp;D,
product innovation.

00:15:02.222 --> 00:15:04.430
So you would think it would
come from R&amp;D and product

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:06.450
innovation, but in
fact, it didn't.

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:09.370
This Doritos guacamole
chip came and was

00:15:09.370 --> 00:15:13.010
discovered by the Latino
Employee Resource Network

00:15:13.010 --> 00:15:14.550
at Frito Lay.

00:15:14.550 --> 00:15:17.410
So the Latino Network
typically comes together

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:19.170
for employee engagement.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:20.546
And when they came
together, they

00:15:20.546 --> 00:15:22.961
said, well, we don't want to
just connect with each other.

00:15:22.961 --> 00:15:25.250
We actually want to solve
a real business challenge.

00:15:25.250 --> 00:15:27.270
And one of the
things they asked is,

00:15:27.270 --> 00:15:30.880
why don't we have a Doritos
chip for the Latino customer

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:31.720
segment?

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:33.190
So they did research.

00:15:33.190 --> 00:15:35.980
They pitched this idea
to product innovation.

00:15:35.980 --> 00:15:38.020
Product innovation
had never taken ideas

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:39.790
from a diversity network.

00:15:39.790 --> 00:15:41.140
They ended up trying it.

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:43.460
It was $100 million product.

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:46.670
Then the Asian network says,
hey, we want to do this, too.

00:15:46.670 --> 00:15:48.920
They came up with
a curry chip that's

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:50.630
a best seller throughout Asia.

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:53.160
And today, the
company systematically

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:55.710
brings together every
single diversity network

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:58.560
to come up with product ideas
for their target segment.

00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:03.610
So what began as one informal
network that wasn't set up

00:16:03.610 --> 00:16:06.600
to come up with product
ideas, when combined,

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:09.560
was able to help the
business and also then

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:13.040
got turned into a more
systematic, sustained effort

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:14.550
throughout the company.

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:16.480
So these are all
some examples of

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:18.510
some unimaginable
transformations

00:16:18.510 --> 00:16:19.420
in today's world.

00:16:19.420 --> 00:16:22.320
And today's goals
are really, first,

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:25.100
to help you understand what
is connectional intelligence.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:27.160
And I just gave you
a set of examples

00:16:27.160 --> 00:16:31.060
that help to highlight some
of the research that we did

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:33.920
and some of the stories
that we feature in the book.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:35.610
But now I want to
talk a little bit more

00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:39.030
about how can you identify how
connectional intelligence is

00:16:39.030 --> 00:16:43.030
used and learn how to apply
it to your work, to your life,

00:16:43.030 --> 00:16:45.100
to your career here at Google.

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:46.920
So in order to do
that, I want you

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:49.940
to understand what's in it for
you and for your organization.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:52.480
Connectional intelligence
is a leadership skill.

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:55.740
But it has huge applications
for business results,

00:16:55.740 --> 00:16:57.740
whether it's growing
talent, whether it's

00:16:57.740 --> 00:16:59.990
driving growth,
managing risks, enabling

00:16:59.990 --> 00:17:02.840
those interdisciplinary
breakthroughs.

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:05.609
And the most important thing
about connectional intelligence

00:17:05.609 --> 00:17:08.720
is it's a human skill that
can be used by anyone, that

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:11.210
can be used by an intern
at Google, by the CEO,

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:13.109
by someone starting
out, by someone

00:17:13.109 --> 00:17:16.530
in a siloed function that
might see a new way of solving

00:17:16.530 --> 00:17:20.349
a problem in a unique
way that might actually

00:17:20.349 --> 00:17:25.060
help many more than you
might have ever thought.

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:27.300
So in order to
describe that, there

00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:29.400
are five fundamental
capabilities

00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:33.800
of connectional intelligence--
curiosity, combination,

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.860
courage, community,
and combustion.

00:17:36.860 --> 00:17:39.860
And let me go through each to
give you a better feel of this.

00:17:39.860 --> 00:17:41.660
So the first is curiosity.

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:43.810
And curiosity from a
connectional intelligence

00:17:43.810 --> 00:17:47.830
perspective is the ability
to broaden your perspective,

00:17:47.830 --> 00:17:50.340
to ask a different
set of questions

00:17:50.340 --> 00:17:52.170
before you solve a problem.

00:17:52.170 --> 00:17:54.900
So in the case of
Oreo, they truly

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:57.790
have the curiosity
to ask, how might we

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:01.130
get everyone ready to act
when it really matters?

00:18:01.130 --> 00:18:03.250
That ad could have
taken six months

00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:05.820
to create and
hundreds of thousands,

00:18:05.820 --> 00:18:07.470
if not millions, of dollars.

00:18:07.470 --> 00:18:10.360
But instead, they focused
on being prepared.

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:12.960
To asked the question, how can
we be prepared and relevant

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:14.600
when it matters most?

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:17.820
And another example of
curiosity is a story

00:18:17.820 --> 00:18:21.530
that we feature in the book
about a man named Ron Wallace.

00:18:21.530 --> 00:18:23.320
That man is Ron Wallace.

00:18:23.320 --> 00:18:27.710
And ladies and gentlemen, that
is his 2,000-pound pumpkin.

00:18:27.710 --> 00:18:31.890
There is something called
be Topsfield Fair, which

00:18:31.890 --> 00:18:34.170
hosts the world's
largest pumpkin contest.

00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:36.540
And every year,
pumpkin farmers compete

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.950
to grow the world's
largest pumpkin.

00:18:38.950 --> 00:18:41.270
And to give you a sense,
from the beginning of time

00:18:41.270 --> 00:18:44.100
to the year 2000, the
largest pumpkin ever grown

00:18:44.100 --> 00:18:45.740
was 1,000 pounds.

00:18:45.740 --> 00:18:51.710
And in a mere 12 years, in 2012,
Ron Wallace grew a 2,000-pound

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:54.250
pumpkin, doubling
the world's record.

00:18:54.250 --> 00:18:55.940
So how did this happen?

00:18:55.940 --> 00:18:58.760
Well, Ron Wallace
knew that he had

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:00.960
to connect with
other fields in order

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:04.090
to truly understand how to grow
the world's largest pumpkin.

00:19:04.090 --> 00:19:06.070
So what he did is over
a series of years,

00:19:06.070 --> 00:19:08.440
he first contacted many
scientists around the world,

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:11.930
asking them about new soil
science, new ways of working.

00:19:11.930 --> 00:19:14.550
He also connected with
potato farmers when

00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:17.610
he read about how there was
one specific fungi that potato

00:19:17.610 --> 00:19:20.980
farmers used to radically
expand the size of potatoes,

00:19:20.980 --> 00:19:22.695
that he then tried
with pumpkins,

00:19:22.695 --> 00:19:25.410
and it radically grew
the size of pumpkins.

00:19:25.410 --> 00:19:29.790
He not only did that, he created
a small circle of association

00:19:29.790 --> 00:19:32.410
in Rhode Island where pumpkin
farmers in Rhode Island

00:19:32.410 --> 00:19:34.540
would come together to
share best practices,

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:36.500
even though they
were all competing

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:38.560
with each other for
the big contest.

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:41.650
And he became a leading
contributor to bigpumpkins.com.

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:45.610
It's a site where pumpkin
farmers around the world

00:19:45.610 --> 00:19:47.460
share best practices.

00:19:47.460 --> 00:19:51.330
So in 2012, through his
connectional intelligence,

00:19:51.330 --> 00:19:54.460
Ron Wallace, in his true
curiosity to ask different

00:19:54.460 --> 00:19:57.600
questions, Ron Wallace wins
the world's largest pumpkin

00:19:57.600 --> 00:20:00.810
contest, growing a
2,000-pound pumpkin.

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:02.700
But the story actually
doesn't stop there.

00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:06.260
In fact today, small-scale
farmers in places like India

00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:08.300
and throughout
sub-Saharan Africa

00:20:08.300 --> 00:20:11.540
are now use using Ron's
discovery of the fungi

00:20:11.540 --> 00:20:15.980
that he found with the potato
farmers to grow big crops,

00:20:15.980 --> 00:20:18.640
because they can't afford
chemical fertilizer.

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:21.810
So in fact today, Ron Wallace is
not only growing big pumpkins.

00:20:21.810 --> 00:20:25.870
He's shaping the global food
supply in big agriculture.

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:29.190
So for you, the
question is really,

00:20:29.190 --> 00:20:31.860
how can you use different
tools and forums

00:20:31.860 --> 00:20:35.040
to broaden your perspective
before you solve problems?

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:37.060
Where do you go to
find information?

00:20:37.060 --> 00:20:39.220
And are there new
forms or new sets

00:20:39.220 --> 00:20:42.790
of places to find and
collect that information?

00:20:42.790 --> 00:20:46.180
The second C I want to
talk about is Courage.

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:48.180
And courage, from the
connectional intelligence

00:20:48.180 --> 00:20:50.440
perspective, is
really this ability

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:54.160
to have difficult and diverse
conversations despite forces

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:56.450
to silence and control.

00:20:56.450 --> 00:20:57.880
One of the great
examples of this

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:59.850
is the Nike Green
Exchange program.

00:20:59.850 --> 00:21:03.960
Has anyone heard of the
Nike Green Exchange program?

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:09.710
Nike a few years ago decided
to release 400 of their patents

00:21:09.710 --> 00:21:13.570
for noncompetitive,
environmentally sustainable use

00:21:13.570 --> 00:21:14.970
by other companies.

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:17.300
And this initiative was
called Green Exchange.

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:19.120
And they did this
because they understood

00:21:19.120 --> 00:21:21.940
that in order to create
change in this industry,

00:21:21.940 --> 00:21:25.300
in order to be a leading
player in sustainability,

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:29.140
they would have to act first and
do something really courageous.

00:21:29.140 --> 00:21:31.560
Soon enough, what
they began to see

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:33.900
is that their patents
were able to be

00:21:33.900 --> 00:21:35.460
used in many different ways.

00:21:35.460 --> 00:21:40.210
For example, one patent in
Nike shoes, one robber patent,

00:21:40.210 --> 00:21:42.030
ended up being used
by a mountain biking

00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:43.650
company in their tires.

00:21:43.650 --> 00:21:45.410
And soon enough,
many other companies

00:21:45.410 --> 00:21:47.810
began to follow,
including Creative Commons

00:21:47.810 --> 00:21:49.740
and Best Buy and beyond.

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:53.170
And they were truly able to
create a new conversation

00:21:53.170 --> 00:21:56.560
about how to better leverage
and share intellectual property

00:21:56.560 --> 00:21:59.260
for non-competitive
and sustainable use.

00:21:59.260 --> 00:22:01.530
And the second
example of courage

00:22:01.530 --> 00:22:04.020
from a connectional
intelligence perspective

00:22:04.020 --> 00:22:07.330
is the story of how Lance
Armstrong got caught doping.

00:22:07.330 --> 00:22:08.930
Does anyone know the story?

00:22:08.930 --> 00:22:11.090
How did Lance
Armstrong get caught

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:14.490
doping in the biking scandal?

00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:17.910
So, many people think
that Lance Armstrong

00:22:17.910 --> 00:22:21.310
got ratted out by his
colleagues, other cyclists.

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:23.300
But in fact, that
did happen, but that

00:22:23.300 --> 00:22:25.480
didn't break the story
in the news altogether.

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:27.200
There was buzz,
but at that time,

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:29.440
Lance Armstrong was a hero.

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:32.670
Everyone wanted to be buddies
with him, because at that time,

00:22:32.670 --> 00:22:34.740
it was the Livestrong campaign.

00:22:34.740 --> 00:22:37.360
So what actually
happened is while there

00:22:37.360 --> 00:22:40.680
was some small buzz without
any major media agency

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:44.620
really pushing this out,
a group of scientists

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:47.070
looked at Lance Armstrong's
cycling history.

00:22:47.070 --> 00:22:49.330
And when they looked
at one specific race,

00:22:49.330 --> 00:22:52.610
they saw roughly no
indication of doping.

00:22:52.610 --> 00:22:54.850
But when they looked
over a 10-year history,

00:22:54.850 --> 00:22:57.360
they saw a very clear
indication of doping.

00:22:57.360 --> 00:22:59.470
And they didn't have a
big media agency that

00:22:59.470 --> 00:23:01.720
wanted to cover this,
so they posted it

00:23:01.720 --> 00:23:04.960
on a small biking blogging
in New Work called New York

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:06.240
Velocity.

00:23:06.240 --> 00:23:09.800
And this biking blog was
filled with bicyclists

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:12.680
who just love to tell the
truth and share in the movement

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:13.940
around cycling.

00:23:13.940 --> 00:23:15.370
So they posted it
there, and then

00:23:15.370 --> 00:23:18.840
a group of basically
cyclist activists

00:23:18.840 --> 00:23:21.650
on Twitter and Facebook
started to spread the story.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:24.360
And it was after a few
months that through spreading

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:27.310
this story, that it actually
broke through in national media

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:31.750
and led to Lance
Armstrong's real opening

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:33.520
in that Oprah interview.

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:35.820
So what truly
happened is that it

00:23:35.820 --> 00:23:38.510
was a combination of
bloggers, of scientists,

00:23:38.510 --> 00:23:41.520
and cyclists who
had no incentive

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:43.590
but to tell the
truth that actually

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:47.010
led to the breakthrough in
discovering the lie that many

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:48.310
of us didn't know.

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:51.450
So the question for
you do is really,

00:23:51.450 --> 00:23:53.610
how are you sparking
courageous conversations

00:23:53.610 --> 00:23:55.160
in your target networks?

00:23:55.160 --> 00:23:57.440
Where are the courageous
conversations happening?

00:23:57.440 --> 00:24:01.210
And how can you engage with
them in an entirely new way that

00:24:01.210 --> 00:24:03.560
might solve the pressing
challenges that you're

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:06.070
facing, just like
Lance Armstrong

00:24:06.070 --> 00:24:10.080
or just like Nike
Green Exchange?

00:24:10.080 --> 00:24:12.340
The third C of
connectional intelligence

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:14.410
is what's called Combination.

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:17.070
And combination by definition
is the root of innovation,

00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:19.690
combining many disparate
ideas to come up

00:24:19.690 --> 00:24:23.260
with an entirely new concept,
product, or innovation.

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:25.310
And some of the best
examples of this, of course,

00:24:25.310 --> 00:24:27.740
is the story of the Doritos
guacamole chip bringing

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:30.070
together the Latinos at
the company to come up

00:24:30.070 --> 00:24:32.020
with a new product idea.

00:24:32.020 --> 00:24:34.120
But it also happens
in many other forms.

00:24:34.120 --> 00:24:36.240
One example of that is Duolingo.

