00:24:44.350 --> 00:24:45.820
a language learning app.

00:24:45.820 --> 00:24:47.120
It's entirely free.

00:24:47.120 --> 00:24:49.590
It's almost like a free
version of Rosetta Stone.

00:24:49.590 --> 00:24:52.620
But many of you might
not know that while it's

00:24:52.620 --> 00:24:54.930
a free language
learning app, it also

00:24:54.930 --> 00:24:58.970
serves as a crowdsourced
text translation platform.

00:24:58.970 --> 00:25:00.750
So let me explain.

00:25:00.750 --> 00:25:02.970
The founder, Luis
von Ahn of Duolingo,

00:25:02.970 --> 00:25:05.090
understood and
asked the question,

00:25:05.090 --> 00:25:07.650
how can I combine
solving one problem

00:25:07.650 --> 00:25:11.260
and solve an entirely different
problem at the same time?

00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:13.110
So one of the
problems he saw was

00:25:13.110 --> 00:25:17.330
that people around the world
needed to learn new languages.

00:25:17.330 --> 00:25:20.000
And he said, how could I
teach the world new languages

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:21.160
for free?

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:23.570
The second problem
that he saw is

00:25:23.570 --> 00:25:26.870
that many online websites,
whether it was something

00:25:26.870 --> 00:25:32.030
like BuzzFeed or CNN, needed
to effectively translate

00:25:32.030 --> 00:25:36.330
their sites from English to
French or Japanese to Mandarin

00:25:36.330 --> 00:25:37.860
in a very quick way.

00:25:37.860 --> 00:25:40.880
And so what he actually did
is he combined the two needs.

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:44.990
And using Duolingo, when
players play Duolingo,

00:25:44.990 --> 00:25:46.980
becuase it runs
basically as a game,

00:25:46.980 --> 00:25:49.180
they're not just doing
random homework problems

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:51.080
of translating
English to French.

00:25:51.080 --> 00:25:53.690
They're actually
translating news websites.

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:56.480
So when a certain
aggregate amount of people

00:25:56.480 --> 00:26:01.200
translate the game at the
same time in the correct way,

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:05.030
it automatically translates
news websites around the world.

00:26:05.030 --> 00:26:09.220
So when you think about this,
how might you be combining?

00:26:09.220 --> 00:26:11.882
Just like the Doritos
guacamole chip and Duolingo,

00:26:11.882 --> 00:26:13.840
how are you combining
information and knowledge

00:26:13.840 --> 00:26:15.960
from inside and
outside your workplace?

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:18.210
Where might you be able
to solve one problem

00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:21.070
and solve an entirely different
problem at the same time

00:26:21.070 --> 00:26:24.230
by combining needs in a new way?

00:26:24.230 --> 00:26:27.600
The fourth C of interconnection
all intelligence is Community.

00:26:27.600 --> 00:26:30.090
And community is
the root of the idea

00:26:30.090 --> 00:26:34.010
of bringing people together
to care, to spark, to inspire

00:26:34.010 --> 00:26:34.790
together.

00:26:34.790 --> 00:26:37.590
And one of my favorite
stories from our book

00:26:37.590 --> 00:26:39.800
is a story at Colgate.

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:42.960
A few years ago, Colgate
had a big science problem.

00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:44.460
They had developed
a new fluoride,

00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:46.209
and they were trying
to get their fluoride

00:26:46.209 --> 00:26:47.293
into their new toothpaste.

00:26:47.293 --> 00:26:49.250
But there was something
wrong, and the fluoride

00:26:49.250 --> 00:26:51.400
was getting stuck in the
mechanical equipment,

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:52.970
and it wasn't meshing well.

00:26:52.970 --> 00:26:54.660
And all the best
chemists of the company

00:26:54.660 --> 00:26:55.900
were trying to figure this out.

00:26:55.900 --> 00:26:56.899
And they had difficulty.

00:26:56.899 --> 00:26:58.660
And it was costing
them a lot of money,

00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:03.150
because they couldn't get the
new product out to market.

00:27:03.150 --> 00:27:06.180
So what they decided
to do is they

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:09.660
decided to post this
question in an anonymous way

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:11.720
on a website called InnoCentive.

00:27:11.720 --> 00:27:14.160
Anyone here know
what InnoCentive is?

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:17.360
InnoCentive is a website
of inventors, hackers,

00:27:17.360 --> 00:27:18.760
problem solvers,
people that just

00:27:18.760 --> 00:27:21.130
want to solve unique problems.

00:27:21.130 --> 00:27:23.860
So what they did is they
posted it on the site,

00:27:23.860 --> 00:27:26.780
and within just a few
days, a physicist named

00:27:26.780 --> 00:27:29.470
Ed Melcarek looked
at the site and said,

00:27:29.470 --> 00:27:30.860
this isn't a chemistry problem.

00:27:30.860 --> 00:27:32.160
This is a physics problem.

00:27:32.160 --> 00:27:33.860
It's about chargeback particles.

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:35.220
You charge the fluoride one way.

00:27:35.220 --> 00:27:36.980
You charge the
toothpaste the other.

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:38.760
Instantly, the
problem was solved,

00:27:38.760 --> 00:27:42.790
saving the company a lot of
money, but not only doing that,

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:45.220
really allowing them to
see how they could leverage

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:48.400
a new type of network to solve
a problem that they couldn't

00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:49.650
solve internally.

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:52.350
And when we interviewed
Ed Melcarek for the book,

00:27:52.350 --> 00:27:54.776
one of the things he
said is that he may never

00:27:54.776 --> 00:27:56.650
have been hired by
Colgate, because he didn't

00:27:56.650 --> 00:27:58.420
have the traditional resume.

00:27:58.420 --> 00:28:02.100
So what we can actually do is
we can engage new communities

00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:05.310
in ways that we never would
have imagined that can actually

00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:08.500
help us solve the problems
we're facing in real time.

00:28:08.500 --> 00:28:11.070
The second story I'd
like to share is Uber.

00:28:11.070 --> 00:28:13.440
Who here knows what Uber is?

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:15.990
Everyone's hands raised, right?

00:28:15.990 --> 00:28:19.250
So when you end an
Uber ride, what's

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:21.230
the last thing you do
before you leave the car?

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:23.480
What's the last thing you
have to do to close the ride

00:28:23.480 --> 00:28:25.570
and get your receipt?

00:28:25.570 --> 00:28:27.134
Tell me.

00:28:27.134 --> 00:28:28.050
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:28.050 --> 00:28:29.716
ERICA DHAWAN: Yes,
you rate your driver.

00:28:29.716 --> 00:28:31.600
And what does your driver do?

00:28:31.600 --> 00:28:32.570
AUDIENCE: Rate.

00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:34.800
ERICA DHAWAN: Yes, the
driver is rating you

00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:36.750
while you're rating your driver.

00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:38.860
And the reason why
this is important

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:42.510
is because if you are not
a great customer on Uber,

00:28:42.510 --> 00:28:45.730
you could, at a certain
point, get kicked off.

00:28:45.730 --> 00:28:48.110
Because for the first
time, really, there's

00:28:48.110 --> 00:28:50.450
optimal nodes flowing
to optimal resources

00:28:50.450 --> 00:28:52.700
in a two-way community
where we're really

00:28:52.700 --> 00:28:55.060
rating each other
in a way to improve

00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:57.230
our behaviors over time.

00:28:57.230 --> 00:28:59.486
And so as we think
about the communities

00:28:59.486 --> 00:29:01.360
of the future in a
connectionally intelligent

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:05.760
mindset, it's really about how
might you create the incentive

00:29:05.760 --> 00:29:07.520
structure to allow
people to care,

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:10.920
to spark, and inspire
together, but also

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:13.950
allow for a systematic
way, just like Uber is,

00:29:13.950 --> 00:29:15.720
to bring the right
set of customers

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:17.920
with the right drivers together?

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:20.500
So I really want
you to think about,

00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:23.480
when you're solving
a problem today,

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:25.730
one way to do it would be
through the Colgate example.

00:29:25.730 --> 00:29:27.354
How might you be
leveraging communities

00:29:27.354 --> 00:29:28.640
outside your existing network?

00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:31.139
And another way would be, how
are you creating the incentive

00:29:31.139 --> 00:29:35.010
structures for communities
to act in the most

00:29:35.010 --> 00:29:37.360
efficient, productive way?

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:39.980
The fifth C is Combustion.

00:29:39.980 --> 00:29:42.140
And combustion from a
connectionally intelligent

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:45.080
perspective is this ability
to mobilize resources

00:29:45.080 --> 00:29:47.310
in pursuit of a large goal.

00:29:47.310 --> 00:29:49.300
One of the examples
of combustion

00:29:49.300 --> 00:29:51.436
is a story about SAP.

00:29:51.436 --> 00:29:56.330
A series of years ago, SAP had a
big customer call waiting list.

00:29:56.330 --> 00:29:58.827
They were overwhelmed with
customer service costs.

00:29:58.827 --> 00:30:00.410
And so one of the
experiments they did

00:30:00.410 --> 00:30:04.000
is they created an open,
peer-to-peer customer platform

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.760
where any customer
could actually

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.060
ask any other customer a
question about the product

00:30:08.060 --> 00:30:09.040
or service.

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:12.160
And over 100,000 people
used it back in the day.

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:14.890
Today, over two million
people have used the site.

00:30:14.890 --> 00:30:17.380
The average response
time is 16 minutes.

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:21.530
99% of queries are answered
correctly within 24 hours.

00:30:21.530 --> 00:30:26.410
But the other thing that really
led to this platform combusting

00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:30.071
is it's one of the top ways for
SAP to identify the products

00:30:30.071 --> 00:30:32.445
and services that they should
be marketing and delivering

00:30:32.445 --> 00:30:33.220
in the future.

00:30:33.220 --> 00:30:35.250
Because they truly
understand and have

00:30:35.250 --> 00:30:38.960
the intelligence of what
customers are really asking for

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:40.340
and what they need.

00:30:40.340 --> 00:30:43.160
The second example of
combustion is the story

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:45.220
of My Starbucks platform.

00:30:45.220 --> 00:30:48.800
Has anyone seen this
platform or know what it is?

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:50.880
So who knows what the
Starbucks green stick

00:30:50.880 --> 00:30:56.000
is that you put in your coffee?

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.454
Does anyone know what that is?

00:30:58.454 --> 00:30:59.370
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:59.370 --> 00:31:00.369
KATHRIN O'SULLIVAN: Yes.

00:31:00.369 --> 00:31:02.250
So Starbucks has a green stick.

00:31:02.250 --> 00:31:03.600
It's called a swizzle stopper.

00:31:03.600 --> 00:31:06.790
And it's used to make sure
that your coffee doesn't spill.

00:31:06.790 --> 00:31:10.110
And for many people, it's
an iconic brand component

00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:12.682
for Starbucks because
it's so well known.

00:31:12.682 --> 00:31:14.140
And many people
don't know, though,

00:31:14.140 --> 00:31:16.970
that it actually came as
an idea from a customer

00:31:16.970 --> 00:31:20.220
through something called the
My Starbucks platform, which

00:31:20.220 --> 00:31:24.250
is a crowdsourcing platform
where customers can share

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:26.912
their ideas for the
store, for products

00:31:26.912 --> 00:31:29.370
that they should be delivering,
for different services they

00:31:29.370 --> 00:31:30.500
should be offering.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:32.437
And today, Starbucks
implements hundreds

00:31:32.437 --> 00:31:33.520
of these ideas every year.

00:31:33.520 --> 00:31:36.250
They get thousands of ideas.

00:31:36.250 --> 00:31:39.090
And it's a top way, as
well, to truly combust,

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:41.940
just like the case with
the green stick, which

00:31:41.940 --> 00:31:46.350
is an iconic model for
the Starbucks brand today.

00:31:46.350 --> 00:31:48.800
So for you, the
question is really,

00:31:48.800 --> 00:31:51.410
how are you going to mobilize
your networks to collaborate

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:52.420
to achieve a goal?

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:54.510
When you may start an
initiative for one way,

00:31:54.510 --> 00:31:57.290
just like Ron Wallace was trying
to grow the world's largest

00:31:57.290 --> 00:32:02.270
pumpkin or the legal
associates were just

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:04.890
trying to work
faster, how might it

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:07.930
combust in an entirely
different way that could really

00:32:07.930 --> 00:32:10.290
help others and
outside networks,

00:32:10.290 --> 00:32:12.300
whether it's inside Google,
outside with clients

00:32:12.300 --> 00:32:16.140
and customers to solve your
most pressing challenges?

00:32:16.140 --> 00:32:19.000
And so what I share
now is that when

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.020
we think about connectional
intelligence, it's not new.

00:32:22.020 --> 00:32:24.820
The great leaders of
our time in history

00:32:24.820 --> 00:32:27.170
have had very high
connectional intelligence,

00:32:27.170 --> 00:32:30.980
whether it was Marie Curie or
Ben Franklin or Mahatma Gandhi.

00:32:30.980 --> 00:32:34.760
But today, and as we know
here as leaders at Google,

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:37.450
the scale, depth, and
breadth of our connection

00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:38.860
is radically different.

00:32:38.860 --> 00:32:40.540
And it's changing
the way that we

00:32:40.540 --> 00:32:44.800
solve problems, not only the way
that we might use technology,

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:48.024
but how we think and act,
mobilize resources, have

00:32:48.024 --> 00:32:50.190
the courage to connect with
people around the world,

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:52.870
have the curiosity to
ask different questions

00:32:52.870 --> 00:32:56.360
and then combine those
ideas in new ways.

00:32:56.360 --> 00:32:59.530
And when you think about
connectional intelligence, what

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:01.840
you'll understand in the
book is that it's best

00:33:01.840 --> 00:33:03.510
to think about it
at different levels.

00:33:03.510 --> 00:33:05.140
So the first level
is the power of one,

00:33:05.140 --> 00:33:06.760
is you as an individual.

00:33:06.760 --> 00:33:09.250
How can you use your own
connectional intelligence

00:33:09.250 --> 00:33:12.040
get big things done, just
like Ron Wallace did,

00:33:12.040 --> 00:33:14.876
a pumpkin farmer, and
for each and every one

00:33:14.876 --> 00:33:17.420
of you, whether it's working
your way up or solving

00:33:17.420 --> 00:33:19.950
or launching a big product?

00:33:19.950 --> 00:33:22.550
And so as you think about that,
what you'll find in the book

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:25.310
is a connectional intelligence
quiz, where you can actually

00:33:25.310 --> 00:33:28.720
assess how and where you're
using connectional intelligence

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:30.740
in your work and in your life.

00:33:30.740 --> 00:33:33.460
The second type are
the power of tens,

00:33:33.460 --> 00:33:35.340
so the power of small teams.

00:33:35.340 --> 00:33:38.850
This is the Oreo team that
said, we need to come together,

00:33:38.850 --> 00:33:40.570
and it's when we're
acting together

00:33:40.570 --> 00:33:43.000
in this relevant and fast
way that we're really going

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:44.900
to get something big done.

00:33:44.900 --> 00:33:48.880
And the third type is
the power of thousands.

00:33:48.880 --> 00:33:52.800
And the power of thousands
here is really this idea

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:56.010
that Colgate harnessed when
they launched and sent out

00:33:56.010 --> 00:33:58.780
a question to a large
network of solvers.

00:33:58.780 --> 00:34:01.560
And from those
thousands, they were

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:05.100
able to scan and source it
and find the physicist that

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:07.060
was able to help
them truly break

00:34:07.060 --> 00:34:09.210
through a difficult challenge.

00:34:09.210 --> 00:34:11.520
So as you think
about the future--

00:34:11.520 --> 00:34:14.489
and I started the talk
talking about the next wave

00:34:14.489 --> 00:34:15.969
in the future.

00:34:15.969 --> 00:34:21.139
And I also was talking about
redefining the next generation

00:34:21.139 --> 00:34:24.500
of millennials, not just as an
age, but as a mindset shift,

00:34:24.500 --> 00:34:27.050
that we are in an age where
actually some of our greatest

00:34:27.050 --> 00:34:30.040
connectional intelligence might
even come from our youngest.

00:34:30.040 --> 00:34:32.750
And so in order to forge
a new way of thinking

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:35.889
across generations, we
need senior leaders,

00:34:35.889 --> 00:34:37.940
and we need younger
leaders to come together

00:34:37.940 --> 00:34:40.929
to act together in
new ways of problem

00:34:40.929 --> 00:34:44.350
solving just like we saw
when the productivity

00:34:44.350 --> 00:34:47.090
idea from the legal
associates is now changing

00:34:47.090 --> 00:34:49.550
the way the firm is
thinking about productivity

00:34:49.550 --> 00:34:50.840
in the future.

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:53.960
And so when you use
connectional intelligence,

00:34:53.960 --> 00:34:55.960
you'll find that it will
benefit your customers,

00:34:55.960 --> 00:35:00.640
your constituents, but also the
planet and larger societies.

00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:03.270
And it can be used by
anyone in your workplace,

00:35:03.270 --> 00:35:06.090
whether it's an individual,
a small team, or a larger

00:35:06.090 --> 00:35:07.430
crowd or network.

00:35:07.430 --> 00:35:10.230
And what you'll find when you
harness connection intelligence

00:35:10.230 --> 00:35:12.350
and you read more
stories in the book,

00:35:12.350 --> 00:35:15.920
you'll find that it will help
you move from this idea of just

00:35:15.920 --> 00:35:16.680
serendipity.

00:35:16.680 --> 00:35:18.410
And we all love serendipity.

00:35:18.410 --> 00:35:21.350
It's the way some of the
magic happens at places

00:35:21.350 --> 00:35:22.760
here like at Google.

00:35:22.760 --> 00:35:25.340
But it will help you
create more intention,

00:35:25.340 --> 00:35:28.140
a more strategic
way of accelerating

00:35:28.140 --> 00:35:31.410
more of those
serendipitous reactions.

00:35:31.410 --> 00:35:35.700
And as we saw with the story
of the Oreo Super Bowl tweet,

00:35:35.700 --> 00:35:37.620
luck comes to the prepared.

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:40.090
So how can you create
a more systematic way

00:35:40.090 --> 00:35:42.550
of leveraging the connections
and networks around you,

00:35:42.550 --> 00:35:45.380
whether it's people,
ideas, or resources?

00:35:45.380 --> 00:35:48.200
So in the book,
what you'll find is

00:35:48.200 --> 00:35:51.650
that we talk about three types
of connectional intelligence.

00:35:51.650 --> 00:35:55.390
And the way I'll help you frame
this that 10 years ago, Malcom

00:35:55.390 --> 00:35:58.930
Gladwell coined the concept of
a connector as one of the three

00:35:58.930 --> 00:36:01.360
ways that create
the rise of social

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:04.050
epidemics-- the mavens,
the salespeople,

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:05.330
and the connectors.

00:36:05.330 --> 00:36:09.000
And while that idea was quite
revolutionary at the time,

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:10.700
today it's quite outdated.

00:36:10.700 --> 00:36:13.240
Because as we all know,
today we are all connectors.

00:36:13.240 --> 00:36:15.100
In fact, we are over-connected.

00:36:15.100 --> 00:36:18.730
So how do we get big things
done through our connections?

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:20.270
And what we found
in our research is

00:36:20.270 --> 00:36:23.920
that in today's world, it's not
about being a connector or not,

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:26.130
it's what type of
connector you are.

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:28.040
And there are three
types of connectors,

